1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:05,290
So today I want to share with you an intriguing
scalping trading strategy.

2
00:00:05,290 --> 00:00:10,860
This strategy leverages a simple yet powerful
phenomenon - that a market’s open price

3
00:00:10,860 --> 00:00:15,420
sometimes matches its highest or lowest point
for the day.

4
00:00:15,420 --> 00:00:18,640
When this occurs, it creates a scalping opportunity.

5
00:00:18,640 --> 00:00:27,279
You see, on such a day, the market has essentially
revealed where it sees strong support or resistance.

6
00:00:27,279 --> 00:00:31,269
Picture this - the open price matches the
initial low.

7
00:00:31,269 --> 00:00:36,350
This tells us buyers stepped in early and
established a clear support, showing where

8
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:39,300
they'll defend the price going forward.

9
00:00:39,300 --> 00:00:46,200
Similarly, an open equal to the high indicates
sellers wasted no time capping further upwards

10
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:49,680
moves, laying out a firm resistance.

11
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:54,730
These congruent levels provide prime entries,
if you trade accordingly.

12
00:00:54,730 --> 00:01:00,480
Think about it…when the open equals the
low, indicated on most platforms by a green

13
00:01:00,480 --> 00:01:06,420
candle, it tells us buyers were able to push
the price up substantially right from the

14
00:01:06,420 --> 00:01:07,420
open.

15
00:01:07,420 --> 00:01:12,400
This demonstrates eager demand exists among
buyers at those levels.

16
00:01:12,400 --> 00:01:17,790
Upside momentum is likely to continue, presenting
a high-probability buy entry.

17
00:01:17,790 --> 00:01:23,860
Conversely, if the open matches the high,
denoted by a red candle, it reveals sellers

18
00:01:23,860 --> 00:01:27,880
could immediately press the price down from
the highs.

19
00:01:27,880 --> 00:01:31,799
This shows willingness to sell around those
areas.

20
00:01:31,799 --> 00:01:36,230
Downside momentum typically follows, offering
a short setup.

21
00:01:36,230 --> 00:01:41,720
When analyzing the markets, it's important
to have the proper tools to easily identify

22
00:01:41,720 --> 00:01:43,440
these signals.

23
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:49,170
Unfortunately, TradingView does not have a
built-in indicator to directly find the signals

24
00:01:49,170 --> 00:01:52,500
of the open matching the low or high.

25
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:57,860
The best solution I've found is to use two
simple indicators together:

26
00:01:57,860 --> 00:02:04,240
First one is the “Open Price” - This displays
a horizontal line marking the open level right

27
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:05,619
on the chart.

28
00:02:05,619 --> 00:02:11,110
It allows a quick visual check to see if open
matches the high or low.

29
00:02:11,110 --> 00:02:17,129
The second indicator is the Opening Range
Breakout - This draws upper and lower lines

30
00:02:17,129 --> 00:02:22,069
connecting the highs and lows of the first
5 minutes of each candle.

31
00:02:22,069 --> 00:02:26,879
So make sure to set it to the 5 minute timeframe
you want to trade.

32
00:02:26,879 --> 00:02:32,151
The two-indicator approach is the cleanest
workaround for easily finding signals, if

33
00:02:32,151 --> 00:02:34,470
you monitor multiple markets.

34
00:02:34,470 --> 00:02:41,390
Now we can visually compare the open price
to the Opening Range high/low lines.

35
00:02:41,390 --> 00:02:46,550
When the open price line tags the low line,
we have a potential buy signal.

36
00:02:46,550 --> 00:02:49,790
If it touches the high line, it's an opportunity
to sell.

37
00:02:49,790 --> 00:02:56,790
It's a bit manual, but that’s the closest
solution within TradingView’s library.

38
00:02:56,790 --> 00:03:03,080
The opening minutes each day will provide
powerful clues about potential scalping opportunities,

39
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:05,810
but also an overall directional bias.

40
00:03:05,810 --> 00:03:11,140
The key point is that when the open matches
the high or low, it suggests there is strong

41
00:03:11,140 --> 00:03:12,440
momentum.

42
00:03:12,440 --> 00:03:15,260
This often leads to increased volatility.

43
00:03:15,260 --> 00:03:22,060
And this presents an opportunity for us, scalpers,
to jump in and capitalize on future swings.

44
00:03:22,060 --> 00:03:26,640
The plan is simple: to catch quick moves based
on the early momentum.

45
00:03:26,640 --> 00:03:33,470
A match between the open price and its highest
or lowest price confirms the likelihood of

46
00:03:33,470 --> 00:03:37,540
an established directional bias for the whole
session.

47
00:03:37,540 --> 00:03:43,409
If the open price drove strongly up from lows,
it raises the probability of an extended bounce

48
00:03:43,409 --> 00:03:46,140
play for trend followers.

49
00:03:46,140 --> 00:03:52,020
Vice versa for an open matching the high,
signaling brief downside potential.

50
00:03:52,020 --> 00:03:57,290
The main advantage of this scalping strategy
is definitely its simplicity.

51
00:03:57,290 --> 00:04:03,200
There's no complex indicators or customized
formulas to configure - just basic pattern

52
00:04:03,200 --> 00:04:08,129
recognition of the open in relation to the
initial high and low.

53
00:04:08,129 --> 00:04:13,370
These signals require little time investment
to analyze and execute on.

54
00:04:13,370 --> 00:04:18,650
You can simply monitor the 5-minute chart
for a few moments at open and immediately

55
00:04:18,650 --> 00:04:21,060
identify an opportunity.

56
00:04:21,060 --> 00:04:26,370
And with potential trades taking shape in
minutes, everything must be streamlined and

57
00:04:26,370 --> 00:04:27,370
optimized.

58
00:04:27,370 --> 00:04:33,840
Usually, a buy or a sell signal is generated
within the first 5 – 15 minutes of the trading

59
00:04:33,840 --> 00:04:34,840
day.

60
00:04:34,840 --> 00:04:40,160
You can play around with the time settings
and see which one works best for you.

61
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:46,620
As volume increases during the first 5 minutes,
it naturally causes prices to oscillate more

62
00:04:46,620 --> 00:04:47,620
widely.

63
00:04:47,620 --> 00:04:53,720
This volatility stretching the highs and lows
creates prime openings for strategic plays.

64
00:04:53,720 --> 00:04:59,210
In this chart, the OPEN price is matching
the DAY's low, and this reveals that smart

65
00:04:59,210 --> 00:05:05,860
institutional players have stepped in overnight
or pre-market to dominate the session.

66
00:05:05,860 --> 00:05:11,660
The sellers didn’t have any power to move
price, not even one tick below the open.

67
00:05:11,660 --> 00:05:14,289
This is very bullish in my opinion.

68
00:05:14,289 --> 00:05:20,080
When the open builds on this support, slowly
but steadily through buying pressure, it frequently

69
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:26,130
initiates an extended trend up, as demand
proved stronger than selling.

70
00:05:26,130 --> 00:05:32,740
In this example, the open matches the high,
suggesting selling pressure dominated early,

71
00:05:32,740 --> 00:05:37,310
with supply outweighing demand right from
the market open.

72
00:05:37,310 --> 00:05:43,080
Often this indicates institutional or other
professional traders were taking profits or

73
00:05:43,080 --> 00:05:46,539
establishing new short positions pre-market.

74
00:05:46,539 --> 00:05:51,900
Seeing this action telegraphed so clearly
in the opening minutes is extremely valuable

75
00:05:51,900 --> 00:05:56,820
for day traders and scalpers looking to ride
the overall trend.

76
00:05:56,820 --> 00:06:03,789
It informs you that big players expect short-term
downward momentum, at least initially.

77
00:06:03,789 --> 00:06:05,790
There are 2 types of entries.

78
00:06:05,790 --> 00:06:12,220
The first one - entering long on the first
push above the first 5 minute candle or immediately

79
00:06:12,220 --> 00:06:14,470
after the candle has formed.

80
00:06:14,470 --> 00:06:20,720
Quality liquidity lies below, and the initial
bounce often has follow-through, as momentum

81
00:06:20,720 --> 00:06:23,900
traders join to ride the wave up.

82
00:06:23,900 --> 00:06:30,389
The second entry - at the 50% Fibonacci retracement
of the initial candle, if the candle is larger

83
00:06:30,389 --> 00:06:31,729
in size.

84
00:06:31,729 --> 00:06:36,970
You see, sometimes it’s better to wait for
a retracement, and then enter, in the direction

85
00:06:36,970 --> 00:06:39,340
of the initial candle.

86
00:06:39,340 --> 00:06:44,960
The aggressive entry comes after you monitor
that first critical 5-minute candle.

87
00:06:44,960 --> 00:06:51,150
By waiting the first candle to form, you allow
the initial dust to settle, while key levels

88
00:06:51,150 --> 00:06:52,150
establish.

89
00:06:52,150 --> 00:06:59,620
For an open equal to the high, I'd set a sell
order a tick below the 5-minute candle's low.

90
00:06:59,620 --> 00:07:05,620
Smart money likely capped upside there, and
a break suggests distribution might persist.

91
00:07:05,620 --> 00:07:13,180
Conversely, an open matching the day's low,
presents buy triggers on a push above the

92
00:07:13,180 --> 00:07:14,289
5-minute high.

93
00:07:14,289 --> 00:07:19,789
The low confirms underlying support, and a
break above signals buyers could maintain

94
00:07:19,789 --> 00:07:23,169
control pushing prices up further.

95
00:07:23,169 --> 00:07:30,000
As you are scalping, always risk small with
tight stops above or below the 5-minute range.

96
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:35,530
And a quick tip - volume-backed breakouts
often spark quick continuation, as momentum

97
00:07:35,530 --> 00:07:37,229
traders pile on.

98
00:07:37,229 --> 00:07:41,150
I kind of prefer the more conservative entry.

99
00:07:41,150 --> 00:07:46,440
Rather than entering signals immediately at
the open of the next candle, I wait for a

100
00:07:46,440 --> 00:07:53,509
retracement back to the midpoint of the opening
5 minute candle, before triggering my entry.

101
00:07:53,509 --> 00:07:59,680
So we enter in the direction of the expected
momentum move at a better price after some

102
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:01,000
pullback.

103
00:08:01,000 --> 00:08:03,830
This improves our risk-reward ratio.

104
00:08:03,830 --> 00:08:10,010
And we avoid potentially getting stopped out
on wider, more volatile opening candles, if

105
00:08:10,010 --> 00:08:13,319
price whipsaws before the impulse begins.

106
00:08:13,319 --> 00:08:19,960
Essentially, we are refining our execution
using the opening candle range as a guide.

107
00:08:19,960 --> 00:08:26,220
Rather than rushing in at the initial 5-minute
candle breakout, waiting for a modest retracement

108
00:08:26,220 --> 00:08:28,819
often helps manage risk better.

109
00:08:28,819 --> 00:08:34,990
So remember this: overextended openings frequently
pull back within the range.

110
00:08:34,990 --> 00:08:40,779
In this case, tightened entries on a pullback
to the midpoint provides a lower-risk second

111
00:08:40,779 --> 00:08:47,600
chance if momentum stalls, without missing
the trade entirely if it resumes swiftly.

112
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:53,920
As for stop placement, keeping them near the
open price often offers the best compromise.

113
00:08:53,920 --> 00:08:59,360
It preserves your capital should the setup
fail, without getting stopped prematurely

114
00:08:59,360 --> 00:09:01,890
from temporary fluctuations.

115
00:09:01,890 --> 00:09:08,600
An alternative is, as swings develop, raise
stops proactively to lock profits and capitalize

116
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,470
on extended moves.

117
00:09:10,470 --> 00:09:15,860
But avoid trailed stops that can whip you
out of positions too hastily.

118
00:09:15,860 --> 00:09:22,170
One of the most precise ways I've found to
extract maximum gains from this scalping strategy

119
00:09:22,170 --> 00:09:29,210
is by factoring in anchored VWAP bands around
that first influential 5-minute open candle.

120
00:09:29,210 --> 00:09:34,290
You add the upper and lower bands, anchored
to the opening price, to highlight potential

121
00:09:34,290 --> 00:09:41,300
areas of support and resistance around the
main VWAP line, as the day progresses.

122
00:09:41,300 --> 00:09:48,230
Now when you enter a scalping trade, you initially
target the 2nd or 3rd VWAP band, in the direction

123
00:09:48,230 --> 00:09:51,490
of your entry, for partial profits.

124
00:09:51,490 --> 00:09:57,170
For example if you go long, you target the
upper anchored VWAP bands for the first take

125
00:09:57,170 --> 00:09:58,510
profit.

126
00:09:58,510 --> 00:10:04,170
If you go short, you aim for the lower VWAP
bands for initial gains.

127
00:10:04,170 --> 00:10:10,029
As price reaches the bands, scale out a portion
of the position, while trailing a stop on

128
00:10:10,029 --> 00:10:16,600
the remainder, to lock in further profits
if momentum continues beyond VWAP.

129
00:10:16,600 --> 00:10:21,720
The key benefit of using the anchored VWAP
bands is they objectively highlight profit

130
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:26,000
areas based on that day's developing value
area.

131
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:33,100
Using multiple exits using VWAP bands makes
your trading far more dynamic and adaptive.

132
00:10:33,100 --> 00:10:39,270
Aiming blindly for a fixed risk - reward ratio
on every trade can be limiting because price

133
00:10:39,270 --> 00:10:42,500
movements and volatility fluctuate.

134
00:10:42,500 --> 00:10:47,350
Some momentum surges will exhaust quickly
after your entry signal.

135
00:10:47,350 --> 00:10:52,029
Others may continue trending strongly beyond
your static target.

136
00:10:52,029 --> 00:10:57,500
This is where adding adaptive exits like VWAP
bands becomes highly useful.

137
00:10:57,500 --> 00:11:03,800
If momentum fizzles out early, the VWAP bands
can alert you to take profits nearer to your

138
00:11:03,800 --> 00:11:05,019
entry.

139
00:11:05,019 --> 00:11:10,730
If the momentum explodes with thrust, the
bands help you trail stops to capture outsized

140
00:11:10,730 --> 00:11:11,769
gains.

141
00:11:11,769 --> 00:11:17,709
Either way, you are basing exits on the real-time
developing market context, rather than just

142
00:11:17,709 --> 00:11:20,910
assuming a pre-set target will be hit.

143
00:11:20,910 --> 00:11:27,040
Remember, you are scalping, so managing risk
smartly is the foundation to your long-term

144
00:11:27,040 --> 00:11:28,519
success.

145
00:11:28,519 --> 00:11:33,750
Consider reducing position size if entering
on wider opening candles.

146
00:11:33,750 --> 00:11:39,519
And trail stops incrementally to lock in profits
as the momentum wave extends.

147
00:11:39,519 --> 00:11:45,940
Learn to scale out partial profits in pieces
rather than exiting the whole trade at once.

148
00:11:45,940 --> 00:11:50,090
And if you want to discover other scalping
strategies, you might want to watch one of

149
00:11:50,090 --> 00:11:50,100
these videos.

